{"title":"Introduction to linear algebra","markdown":{"headingText":"Introduction to linear algebra","containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\nThe book : **Linear Algebra and Optimization for Machine Learning**\n\n## Introduction\n\nWhat is Linear Algebra ? \n\nLinear Algebra is the study of **linear operations** on **vector spaces**.\n\nWhat is a linear operation then ... \n\nLet $V$ and $W$ be vector spaces. \nA function $f: V \\rightarrow W$ is a linear map if for any two vectors $\\textbf{u}$ and $\\textbf{v}$ the mapping is _operation preserving_, that is, it satisfies these conditions: \n\n- _Additivity_ : $f(\\textbf{u} + \\textbf{v}) = f(\\textbf{u}) + f(\\textbf{v})$\n\n- _Homogeneity_ of scalar multiplication : $f(c\\textbf{u}) = c*f(\\textbf{u})$\n\n\nFor example : \n\n\n$$\n\\begin{align*}\n    \\begin{split}\n        \\textbf{a} = [0, 1] \\\\\n        \\textbf{b} = [1 ,1] \\\\\n        \\text{The function } f(a,b) = (3a,b) \\text{works since: }\n    \\end{split}\n\n\n    f(a+b) = f([0,1] + [1,1]) = f([1,2]) = (3,2)\n    f(a) + f(b) = [0,1] + [3,1] = [3,2]\n\n    f(a + [3,3] ) = f([0,1] + [3,3]) = f([3,4]) = [9,4]\n    equal to \n    f(a + [3,3]) = f(a) + f([3,3]) = [0,1] + [9,3] = [9,4]\n\n\n    It preserves the multiplication, for ex lambda = 2: \n    f(\\lambda * a) = f(2*[0,1]) = f([0,2]) = [0,2]\n    Which is the same as : \n    f(\\lambda * a) = \\lambda * f(a) = 2 * [0,1] = [0,2]\n\n\\end{align*}\n$$\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":false,"echo":true,"output":true,"warning":true,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-ht